":"Right Handed","plectrum_tech":"Unknown","posture":"Standing","performance_mode":"Solo","semantic":"N/A","gender":"Male (Certain)","location_info":"Non-specific"}},{"type":"Feature","id":8,"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[44.06148107000007,34.319223830000055]},"properties":{"OBJECTID":8,"id":8,"name":"Seven Warriors","latitude":34.319223829999999,"longitude":44.061481069999999,"description":"“Unfinished” Kudurru, Kassite period, attributed to the reign of Melishipak, 1186–1172 B.C.E., found in Susa, where it had been taken as war booty in the 12th century B.C.E. (Louvre, Paris; photo:\u00A0Steven Zucker [https://flic.kr/p/osBGkR] , CC BY-NC-SA 2.0).\nDetail of one of seven warrior-lutenists, register 2/4 of carved limestone kudurru. Kassite period, Reign of Melišippak II, c. 1186-1172 BC.  \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cimg src=images/A-M-008-V.png width=\\\"200\\\"\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e","period":"Antiquity","data_type":"Visual Document","century":"12th Century BCE","geography":"Mesopotamia (Iraq)","culture":"\u00A0Babylonian - Ancient Mesopotamian","neck_length":"Long Necked","soundbox_type":"Bowl","material":"Unknown","string_count":"Unknown","tuning_info":"1/2 Possible Tuning Peg/s","fret_info":"Unknown","visual_design":"No Design","performance_type":"Religious Based Context/Performance","right_hand_tech":"Unknown","left_hand_tech":"Unknown","handedness":"Right Handed","plectrum_tech":"Unknown","posture":"Standing","performance_mode":"Collective","semantic":"N/A","gender":"Male (Certain)","location_info":"Non-specific"}},{"type":"Feature","id":9,"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[67.300499590000072,37.255128840000054]},"properties":{"OBJECTID":9,"id":9,"name":"Central Asia Evidences I","latitude":37.255128839999998,"longitude":67.300499590000001,"description":"Three musicians (a drummer, a lutenist and a harper) bordered by acanthus leaves, from the Airtam Frieze, an artwork in the Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg, Russia. The artwork was originally part of the entrance to a Buddhist temple. \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cimg src=images/A-M-009-V.png width=\\\"200\\\"\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e","period":"Antiquity","data_type":"Visual Document","century":"1st Century BCE","geography":"\u00A0Central Asia (Uzbekistan)","culture":"Kushan Bactria ","neck_length":"Short Necked","soundbox_type":"Box","material":"Unknown","string_count":"4","tuning_info":"Unknown","fret_info":"Unknown","visual_design":"No Design","performance_type":"Religious Based Context/Performance","right_hand_tech":"Unknown","left_hand_tech":"Unknown","handedness":"Right Handed","plectrum_tech":"Unknown","posture":"Seated","performance_mode":"Collective","semantic":"N/A","gender":"Female (Certain)","location_info":"Temple"}},{"type":"Feature","id":10,"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[38.480371750000074,37.579915320000055]},"properties":{"OBJECTID":10,"id":10,"name":"First Evidence From Anatolia","latitude":37.579915319999998,"longitude":38.480371750000003,"description":"One of the oldest pieces of evidence regarding bağlama-type instruments found in Anatolia is a painted pottery fragment discovered in Samsat/Adıyaman (Dinçol 2003: 30).\n\nIt dates back to the Old Hittite State period, i.e., 1650-1620 BC (Sipahi 2004: 30-31). \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cimg src=images/A-A-010-V.png width=\\\"200\\\"\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e","period":"Antiquity","data_type":"Visual Document","century":"17th Century BCE","geography":"\u00A0Anatolia (Turkey)","culture":"Hittite","neck_length":"Long Necked","soundbox_type":"Bowl","material":"Unknown","string_count":"Unknown","tuning_info":"Unknown","fret_info":"Unknown","visual_design":"No Design","performance_type":"Secular Context/Performance","right_hand_tech":"Unknown","left_hand_tech":"Unknown","handedness":"Right Handed","plectrum_tech":"Unknown","posture":"Standing","performance_mode":"Solo","semantic":"N/A","gender":"Male (Not Certain)","location_info":"Non-specific"}},{"type":"Feature","id":11,"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[33.562054520000061,40.408670220000033]},"properties":{"OBJECTID":11,"id":11,"name":"İnandık Vase","latitude":40.408670219999998,"longitude":33.562054519999997,"description":"The vase unearthed at İnandık Tepe, dating to approximately 1600 BC, depicts two separate lute-type instrument players (Dinçol 2003: 30-31).\n\nThe İnandık Vase, one of the famous examples of Hittite depiction and musical art, plays an important role as an indicator for the traces of the lute in Anatolia and among the Hittites. \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cimg src=images/A-A-011-V.png width=\\\"200\\\"\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e","period":"Antiquity","data_type":"Visual Document","century":"17th Century BCE","geography":"\u00A0Anatolia (Turkey)","culture":"Hittite","neck_length":"Long Necked","soundbox_type":"Bowl","material":"Unknown","string_count":"Unknown","tuning_info":"Unknown","fret_info":"Unknown","visual_design":"No Design","performance_type":"Religious Based Context/Performance","right_hand_tech":"Unknown","left_hand_tech":"Unknown","handedness":"Right Handed","plectrum_tech":"Unknown","posture":"Standing","performance_mode":"Collective","semantic":"N/A","gender":"Male (Certain)","location_info":"Holy Wedding Ceramony"}},{"type":"Feature","id":12,"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[34.696912800000064,40.235184050000043]},"properties":{"OBJECTID":12,"id":12,"name":"Alacahöyük Orthostat","latitude":40.235184050000001,"longitude":34.6969128,"description":"The wall relief / orthostat found in Alacahöyük, Çorum, is noteworthy for its depiction of a lute-type instrument with tassels and frets.\n\nIts body form differs from that of contemporary tanbura-type instruments, exhibiting a more segmented structure. \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cimg src=images/A-A-012-V.png width=\\\"200\\\"\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e","period":"Antiquity","data_type":"Visual Document","century":"15th Century BCE","geography":"\u00A0Anatolia (Turkey)","culture":"Hittite","neck_length":"Long Necked","soundbox_type":"Other","material":"Unknown","string_count":"Unknown","tuning_info":"Unknown","fret_info":"Possible Evidence","visual_design":"No Design","performance_type":"Secular Context/Performance","right_hand_tech":"Unknown","left_hand_tech":"Unknown","handedness":"Right Handed","plectrum_tech":"Unknown","posture":"Standing","performance_mode":"Collective","semantic":"N/A","gender":"Male (Not Certain)","location_info":"City Square"}},{"type":"Feature","id":13,"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[34.608218070000078,40.025024020000046]},"properties":{"OBJECTID":13,"id":13,"name":"Hittite Funeral Rituals Texts","latitude":40.025024019999996,"longitude":34.608218069999999,"description":"It is said that the Hittites had the oldest indigenous writing culture in Anatolia (Hawkins 1986: 363-364).\nThis makes them the most important source of written information about Ancient Anatolia.\nHittite cuneiform tablets show that the Hittites placed particular importance on the performance of musical instruments in birth and death rituals, healing and worship rituals, and ceremonies and festivals such as weddings and victories (Hitit Portalı: Myths – Rituals; Masalcı Şahin 2018: 27-39).\nIt was initially suggested that the Sumerian word «(GIŠ2)ŠÀ.A.TAR», used in the geography of ancient Mesopotamia, referred to a stringed musical instrument (Masalcı Şahin 2016: 83).\nLater, this word, which is encountered in Hittite cuneiform tablets with its new reading as «TIBULA», is thought by many researchers to describe a lute-type instrument (Masalcı Şahin 2016: 86).\nThe instrument referred to as «TIBULA», which is thought to be a lute-type instrument, is written to have accompanied the singer in the Hittite text titled «Death Ritual Day 1-2» (CTH 450.1.1.1, 180’.. Line, Kapełuś, Hethiter.net, online).\n\nIn this respect, it is reminiscent of the ritual of playing the saz (a stringed instrument) after the death of a person in the Turkish minstrel tradition (Masalcı Şahin 2018: 138, 139).\n\nThe word «TIBULA» also appears in the text related to the KI.LAM festival: Kbo X 24 / Masalcı Şahin 2018: 266 \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cimg src=images/A-A-013-V.png width=\\\"200\\\"\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e","period":"Antiquity","data_type":"\u00A0Written Document","century":"15th Century BCE","geography":"\u00A0Anatolia (Turkey)","culture":"Hittite","neck_length":"Unknown","soundbox_type":"Unknown","material":"Unknown","string_count":"Unknown","tuning_info":"Unknown","fret_info":"Unknown","visual_design":"Unknown","performance_type":"Religious Based Context/Performance","right_hand_tech":"Unknown","left_hand_tech":"Unknown","handedness":"Unknown","plectrum_tech":"Unknown","posture":"Unknown","performance_mode":"Collective","semantic":"Hittite Funeral Rituals Texts","gender":"Male (Certain)","location_info":"City Square"}},{"type":"Feature","id":14,"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[37.997930620000034,36.833435050000048]},"properties":{"OBJECTID":14,"id":14,"name":"Karkamış/Kargamış Orthostat (Procession)","latitude":36.833435049999999,"longitude":37.997930619999998,"description":"The Karkamış wall relief depicts a dancer and musicians, and shows the playing of a tasseled lute-like instrument.\nThis provides evidence of the playing of lute-type instruments during the Late Hittite period. \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cimg src=images/A-A-014-V.png width=\\\"200\\\"\u003e \u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e","period":"Antiquity","data_type":"Visual Document","century":"12th Century BCE","geography":"\u00A0Anatolia (Turkey)","culture":"Hittite","neck_length":"Long Necked","soundbox_type":"Bowl","material":"Unknown","string_count":"Unknown","tuning_info":"Unknown","fret_info":"Unknown","visual_design":"Unknown","performance_type":"Secular Context/Performance","right_hand_tech":"Unknown","left_hand_tech":"Unknown","han